1
00:00:00,730 --> 00:00:02,280
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,040 --> 00:00:09,580
Today we'll be looking at the power supply for our Tesla in this little rig.

3
00:00:10,660 --> 00:00:14,440
Here's the schematic of our converter.

4
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:16,460
What are the requirements for it?

5
00:00:17,260 --> 00:00:23,400
The converter is powered from 12 volts, so the system can be started from a single battery.

6
00:00:25,220 --> 00:00:28,680
And it has to stably hold the output voltage.

7
00:00:29,920 --> 00:00:33,720
For that to happen, we'll need feedback.

8
00:00:34,680 --> 00:00:36,780
I'll go into more detail on it now.

9
00:00:37,900 --> 00:00:39,060
How it works.

10
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:42,660
Our converter looks like this.

11
00:00:43,800 --> 00:00:45,640
Such a little gadget, as you can see.

12
00:00:47,500 --> 00:00:50,440
I'll explain part by part what goes where.

13
00:00:51,860 --> 00:00:55,100
The layout isn't too complicated.

14
00:00:55,860 --> 00:01:03,960
Basically, you can use it not just for powering the Tesla, but also as a normal converter for other purposes.

15
00:01:04,260 --> 00:01:08,120
You can easily make one for 220 volts, whatever you need.

16
00:01:08,740 --> 00:01:14,280
It all depends on this transformer, how many turns you wind on the secondary.

17
00:01:15,620 --> 00:01:17,240
Let's go through the schematic.

18
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:22,120
12 volts of power come in.

19
00:01:22,120 --> 00:01:24,120
They reach the capacitor.

20
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:27,800
Our capacitor is 3300 µF, 25 volts.

21
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:32,700
Next, this power is sent to the center tap.

22
00:01:33,300 --> 00:01:36,600
Our converter is push-pull type.

23
00:01:36,980 --> 00:01:41,960
For low voltage, it's the most efficient option.

24
00:01:43,060 --> 00:01:48,120
We have 8 turns per arm going to the secondary winding.

25
00:01:48,260 --> 00:01:52,240
Our secondary winding is wound at 75 turns.

26
00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:56,140
After every 20 turns there's a tap.

27
00:01:56,640 --> 00:01:57,880
Here are those taps.

28
00:01:59,500 --> 00:02:01,820
First, second, and third.

29
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:05,080
So we wound 75 turns total.

30
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:07,360
What do we use as the core?

31
00:02:07,720 --> 00:02:11,660
This kind of ferrite ring, mark 2000.

32
00:02:13,420 --> 00:02:16,020
Its dimensions are shown.

33
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:29,200
Hole 16 mm, width 8 mm, and 33 mm outer diameter.

34
00:02:30,720 --> 00:02:31,720
That's plenty.

35
00:02:32,340 --> 00:02:38,600
There's also a choke used here — there it is on the schematic — made on a small little ring.

36
00:02:38,700 --> 00:02:42,880
You can make it on any ring you have.

37
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:46,420
Mark from 1000 to 2000, any of those will do.

38
00:02:47,280 --> 00:02:48,220
What's it for?

39
00:02:49,020 --> 00:02:53,240
This output goes to power the Tesla switch.

40
00:02:54,020 --> 00:03:05,540
So we get sharp voltage transitions here when the switch is operating, plus static potentials show up.

41
00:03:06,140 --> 00:03:12,240
And this choke damps those transitions so they don't feed back into our circuit.

42
00:03:13,580 --> 00:03:24,960
Before the output, we have a non-polar bank capacitor, half a microfarad at 400 volts, to damp those spikes.

43
00:03:25,740 --> 00:03:33,940
On the board, it's made up of 5 capacitors of 0.1 µF each.

44
00:03:34,420 --> 00:03:36,800
And this is the output choke.

45
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:41,860
Let's look at what works and how.

46
00:03:42,740 --> 00:03:52,760
We assemble the converter — nice little chip, UC3825N, in a DIP8 package.

47
00:03:53,620 --> 00:03:59,540
The advantage of this design is that the driver is built in, so you don't need an extra chip.

48
00:04:00,280 --> 00:04:12,020
It's plenty for driving transistors like these in this little package — I think it's the TO-220.

49
00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:15,820
They work great.

50
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:28,100
We've also got discharge resistance of one kiloohm here. Basically all standard stuff, you've seen this kind of wiring in previous videos.

51
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:32,520
You don't need reverse diodes here, no extra wiring.

52
00:04:32,520 --> 00:04:38,340
It works great — our circuit doesn't have such high requirements.

53
00:04:39,600 --> 00:04:46,440
Wiring's simple. What else is interesting here?

54
00:04:47,860 --> 00:04:51,800
Let's move on, I think, to the feedback circuit.

55
00:04:52,520 --> 00:05:00,960
Our feedback is built on an optocoupler — the very common PC-817.

56
00:05:02,780 --> 00:05:12,100
We'll zoom in a bit and walk through it.

57
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:22,540
Optocoupler hookup, and we're looking at how it works.

58
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:40,620
We take the supply voltage not from the output capacitor, but from before the choke — before it damps all the spikes from the Tesla switch operation.

59
00:05:42,020 --> 00:05:50,100
The common minus at the output goes to the diode bridge.

60
00:05:50,220 --> 00:05:59,700
The bridge is made from four HER108 diodes in this circuit.

61
00:06:01,240 --> 00:06:05,080
Why did I decide to use a diode bridge here?

62
00:06:05,340 --> 00:06:15,200
Again, we need stability so the feedback isn't shunted by static spikes — we want all that stuff to drain away.

63
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,340
This is really important for this converter to work properly.

64
00:06:19,340 --> 00:06:39,760
In ordinary converters you could get away with one or two diodes, but I decided to put a small diode bridge here. So here's what it looks like — four diodes and the capacitor they feed, 3300 pF at 400 V.

65
00:06:39,760 --> 00:06:43,580
The potential drops onto that 3300 pF, 400 V cap.

66
00:06:44,300 --> 00:06:53,940
With 75 turns wound, this converter gives 130 V at the output.

67
00:06:56,780 --> 00:07:05,340
What do we need to do to pick the right feedback so it works properly?

68
00:07:06,080 --> 00:07:09,400
Ours is built on a divider.

69
00:07:09,940 --> 00:07:24,420
The divider uses a 1 kΩ resistor, then a 15 kΩ trim pot which will set the output voltage that the converter holds.

70
00:07:25,080 --> 00:07:35,900
Plus one more resistor that you'll need to pick depending on the voltage the Tesla will run at.

71
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:49,940
It's marked with an asterisk. For my specific values — if I'm running 130 V output — this resistor is 100 kΩ.

72
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:57,960
If I'm running 70 V at the output, then it comes out to 43 kΩ.

73
00:07:59,580 --> 00:08:03,940
We put a limiting resistor on the optocoupler.

74
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:22,760
Here's how it works: when the output potential reaches a certain value, it goes through the diode bridge, charges the capacitor, and that potential gets divided by the resistor divider.

75
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:24,900
Through that resistor divider.

76
00:08:25,080 --> 00:08:29,840
Then, through the limiting resistor, it reaches the LED inside the optocoupler.

77
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:40,080
The LED triggers — physically sending a light signal to the optotransistor's base.

78
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:50,100
The optotransistor opens, and that gives us a signal from its emitter that lands on pin 1 of the chip.

79
00:08:51,080 --> 00:09:04,620
Pin 1 on this chip is specifically the voltage feedback input. So what does this chip do?

80
00:09:04,760 --> 00:09:12,340
It reduces the signal duty cycle, keeps reducing it until the output potential drops.

81
00:09:12,680 --> 00:09:14,760
So the system stays balanced.

82
00:09:15,380 --> 00:09:17,600
Why do we pick this resistor?

83
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:33,560
If it's wrong for the voltage you're running, your converter might not trigger at a high enough frequency. You won't see it on the load directly, but on a lamp you'll notice flickering.

84
00:09:33,560 --> 00:09:37,340
The lamp will clearly flicker.

85
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,780
Which means the resistor isn't picked right.

86
00:09:40,880 --> 00:09:51,300
Adjust it until the feedback kicks in and the lamp stops flickering. All of this is much clearer on the oscilloscope.

87
00:09:51,500 --> 00:09:53,500
Let's look at how it works next.

88
00:09:55,880 --> 00:10:07,460
Important — this diode bridge: its common minus does not connect to the common minus that powers the chip.

89
00:10:07,980 --> 00:10:15,140
It's a separate section that works specifically with the LED in the optocoupler.

90
00:10:15,820 --> 00:10:35,900
And here's the output from the converter — the diagram shows the bridge input is built on HER508 diodes. You can connect the first, second, or third tap. Wind more turns and you'll have a fourth tap available for higher voltage.

91
00:10:35,900 --> 00:10:40,340
For boosting the voltage.

92
00:10:41,680 --> 00:10:45,900
The output minus here doesn't connect to common either.

93
00:10:46,280 --> 00:10:50,180
That gives us a circuit with inductive isolation.

94
00:10:51,120 --> 00:11:04,040
Our Tesla is isolated from the main circuit. It doesn't affect it with its potential — all the static stuff, the voltage jumps during tuning, etc., stays separate.

95
00:11:08,660 --> 00:11:14,440
We've covered that — now let's look at how it's laid out on the board.

96
00:11:16,380 --> 00:11:17,520
What do we see here?

97
00:11:17,620 --> 00:11:36,960
Here's the input capacitor. Then the chip itself is powered through a choke — there it is on the schematic — so we can filter out ripples and the chip runs cleanly.

98
00:11:36,960 --> 00:11:37,500
For us.

99
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:47,720
Here's the resistor that we change — this is exactly the one marked with the asterisk.

100
00:11:49,160 --> 00:11:54,660
The push-pull goes through 10 Ω to the gates.

101
00:11:55,080 --> 00:11:55,760
Transistors.

102
00:11:55,840 --> 00:12:09,760
I took the transistors out of old computer UPSes — P60 NF06. IRF3205 works well too.

103
00:12:12,760 --> 00:12:15,580
On the arms.

104
00:12:15,760 --> 00:12:20,340
Here's lacquer-insulated wire put into heat shrink.

105
00:12:21,440 --> 00:12:32,500
The converter itself is wound with PVC-insulated wire — 1 mm core, 1.5 mm with the insulation.

106
00:12:33,500 --> 00:12:35,260
What else is interesting?

107
00:12:35,920 --> 00:12:43,380
The transformer output goes to the diode bridge, and from the bridge to the capacitor.

108
00:12:44,060 --> 00:12:49,760
The cap is here — 4700 µF, 200 V.

109
00:12:50,540 --> 00:12:54,460
200 V was enough for me because my converter runs at 130 V.

110
00:12:54,680 --> 00:13:13,220
If you plan on running higher, you pick a bigger capacitor — say with a 50 V margin above what the converter and this pulse transformer can produce.

111
00:13:17,960 --> 00:13:21,300
What else can cause trouble?

112
00:13:21,960 --> 00:13:22,960
This is clear.

113
00:13:23,260 --> 00:13:30,020
By the way, the wiring is simple, but if you look closely at this chip you can also add current protection.

114
00:13:30,840 --> 00:13:34,940
It goes on pin 9, I believe.

115
00:13:37,260 --> 00:13:43,800
Handy chip — you get nice powerful converters out of it, you can even build welding inverters.

116
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:47,240
Really good design choice.

117
00:13:47,880 --> 00:13:58,260
Of course, if you go for welding inverters, you'll need proper drivers here. But for these transistors, this is plenty.

118
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:00,620
It all comes out compact and clean.

119
00:14:01,080 --> 00:14:02,600
No need for a big heat sink.

120
00:14:05,240 --> 00:14:06,940
That covers the main points.

121
00:14:07,060 --> 00:14:10,180
Now let's see how it works.

122
00:14:12,680 --> 00:14:16,700
Here's how we start tuning this converter.

123
00:14:19,660 --> 00:14:22,680
First, we check the connections.

124
00:14:23,820 --> 00:14:32,480
Then, without feeding power to the push-pull arms yet, we check the chip's operation.

125
00:14:32,600 --> 00:14:36,980
We put the oscilloscope on the gates, relative to the center tap.

126
00:14:37,220 --> 00:14:43,520
Check that we have square signals with a pause between them.

127
00:14:44,840 --> 00:14:56,060
This 5 kΩ resistor sets the maximum duty cycle of the pulses that open the transistors.

128
00:14:56,900 --> 00:15:03,620
The resistor on pin 5 is 10 kΩ, and the cap is 2200 pF.

129
00:15:03,960 --> 00:15:06,740
That's our frequency-setting circuit.

130
00:15:07,160 --> 00:15:08,760
What do we do with it?

131
00:15:09,380 --> 00:15:23,940
Start with a 10 kΩ trim pot. After the check, feed power to the push-pull and find this point for your particular core.

132
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:40,800
Sweep the frequency on the chip and watch for the frequency at which your converter has the lowest consumption at idle.

133
00:15:41,140 --> 00:15:43,600
That's the frequency you stay at.

134
00:15:43,740 --> 00:15:52,860
In my case, for my ferrite, that frequency came out around 65 kHz.

135
00:15:54,600 --> 00:16:03,700
Yours might be different, but you want to find the frequency where this ferrite core has the lowest losses.

136
00:16:03,860 --> 00:16:13,260
That's where most of the core material remagnetizes with minimal resistance to the magnetic field.

137
00:16:13,360 --> 00:16:27,140
Then your converter's efficiency is much higher, the transistors and the transformer heat up much less, and the converter has nice characteristics overall.

138
00:16:27,940 --> 00:16:45,100
Once you've found that frequency with the trim pot, desolder it, look at how it was connected, and measure the resistance between those contacts.

139
00:16:46,120 --> 00:16:57,440
Then solder in a regular resistor of that value, or something close.

140
00:16:58,100 --> 00:16:59,480
And that's it, you leave it.

141
00:17:00,880 --> 00:17:04,740
It stays in the circuit for further operation.

142
00:17:04,900 --> 00:17:08,020
You don't need to adjust the frequency anymore.

143
00:17:08,820 --> 00:17:19,340
And the duty cycle trim pot — you can also replace that with a regular resistor.

144
00:17:19,460 --> 00:17:21,620
Much cheaper once you're tuned.

145
00:17:23,020 --> 00:17:27,160
OK, let's see how the thing works.

146
00:17:29,840 --> 00:17:33,840
By the way, the converter turns out pretty powerful.

147
00:17:34,220 --> 00:17:41,180
Right now I've got a 300 W lamp on the output — let's start it up.

148
00:17:43,940 --> 00:17:47,420
We see 47 volts on the lamp.

149
00:17:49,080 --> 00:17:54,840
I'm using the first tap per the schematic.

150
00:17:55,320 --> 00:18:00,800
So on the first tap I get about 70 volts.

151
00:18:01,540 --> 00:18:07,400
Right now the trim pot is set to limit at about 50 volts.

152
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:09,300
I unscrew the lamp.

153
00:18:10,500 --> 00:18:16,660
We see our converter stably holds 50.5 volts at the output.

154
00:18:17,380 --> 00:18:23,500
When the load is connected, there's a tiny sag.

155
00:18:23,680 --> 00:18:25,380
That's a serious load.

156
00:18:26,680 --> 00:18:31,840
I even hooked up two 300 W lamps to it as a test.

157
00:18:31,840 --> 00:18:43,280
And if you're curious, consumption right now is 3 amps at 12.5 volts.

158
00:18:44,380 --> 00:18:46,360
Here are the oscilloscope traces.

159
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:52,380
You can clearly see how the feedback is working.

160
00:18:53,860 --> 00:18:56,840
Let's hit pause and look at this moment.

161
00:18:56,980 --> 00:19:08,100
You can see the signals from the chip don't overlap during dead time, but the duty cycle keeps dropping while feedback is working.

162
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:22,320
We see that when the voltage dropped, duty cycle goes up; voltage rises, then the chip limits the duty cycle again on the channels.

163
00:19:22,800 --> 00:19:24,260
You can see that process clearly.

164
00:19:24,380 --> 00:19:26,960
It runs continuously in this balanced mode.

165
00:19:27,600 --> 00:19:29,700
This is the signal you should get.

166
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:32,380
Interesting jumping pattern.

167
00:19:33,280 --> 00:19:35,300
That's how feedback works.

168
00:19:35,640 --> 00:19:38,720
Now I'll remove the load.

169
00:19:40,980 --> 00:19:41,660
Watch.

170
00:19:42,240 --> 00:19:51,700
I removed the load and the converter switched to pure voltage maintenance mode — holding 50 volts at the output.

171
00:19:52,220 --> 00:19:58,160
The duty cycle is at its minimum for those losses.

172
00:19:58,880 --> 00:20:00,760
Let's look at how it works.

173
00:20:01,820 --> 00:20:13,980
That's exactly what the feedback is for — to hold steady voltage with minimum consumption in this chip's operating mode.

174
00:20:15,280 --> 00:20:25,500
0.03 amps is plenty for maintaining 50 volts at idle for this converter.

175
00:20:26,620 --> 00:20:29,400
The Tesla obviously shouldn't draw that much.

176
00:20:31,020 --> 00:20:36,440
Testing this converter is basically a stress test for it.

177
00:20:37,360 --> 00:20:41,200
300 watts just to confirm everything works.

178
00:20:42,840 --> 00:20:45,920
I also tested it at 130 volts.

179
00:20:46,420 --> 00:20:58,180
With this lamp there's a power sag down to about 125 volts, but on a 25 W lamp it holds perfectly steady.

180
00:20:58,960 --> 00:21:04,360
So you can dial in whatever voltage you want for this converter.

181
00:21:06,940 --> 00:21:15,560
I'll take the 300 W off and now we'll see how the feedback kicks in.

182
00:21:16,440 --> 00:21:17,840
Oscilloscope.

183
00:21:19,760 --> 00:21:21,280
There's our signal.

184
00:21:23,080 --> 00:21:25,880
At peak duty cycle.

185
00:21:26,600 --> 00:21:29,360
Screwing in a 25 W lamp.

186
00:21:30,980 --> 00:21:33,520
Consumption starts now.

187
00:21:34,740 --> 00:21:37,800
The lamp's lit up a bit.

188
00:21:38,920 --> 00:21:43,160
And the chip switched into a pulsating duty cycle mode.

189
00:21:49,670 --> 00:21:56,390
You can see the duty cycle being chopped into bursts.

190
00:21:59,670 --> 00:22:07,870
So the chip works in bursts, with the duty cycle within each burst regulated automatically.

191
00:22:09,110 --> 00:22:10,870
Really nice operating mode.

192
00:22:14,710 --> 00:22:15,850
One more thing.

193
00:22:16,490 --> 00:22:19,910
You want the burst frequency to be as high as possible.

194
00:22:20,090 --> 00:22:28,610
That's also set by the trim pot we looked at earlier with the feedback.

195
00:22:30,030 --> 00:22:40,990
This resistor is really important for quality operation — so your lamp doesn't blink and there are no sharp transitions.

196
00:22:45,430 --> 00:22:48,750
And one more thing to notice.

197
00:22:49,590 --> 00:22:51,390
Let's see how this goes.

198
00:22:52,990 --> 00:22:56,070
Now the trim pot.

199
00:22:57,150 --> 00:23:01,270
The 15 kΩ in the feedback, per schematic.

200
00:23:01,450 --> 00:23:05,410
How they affect voltage regulation.

201
00:23:16,020 --> 00:23:23,100
The voltage drops smoothly as you turn this resistor.

202
00:23:27,280 --> 00:23:37,480
And on the chip you can set whatever supply voltage you need.

203
00:23:38,540 --> 00:23:39,940
You can see we've come down.

204
00:23:40,940 --> 00:23:48,300
From 50 to 33 volts — you can set any trip point you want.

205
00:23:49,540 --> 00:23:53,920
At this mode we have an oscillogram like this.

206
00:24:02,250 --> 00:24:05,010
The lamp doesn't appear to be glowing.

207
00:24:05,130 --> 00:24:08,410
The voltage is too low for it now.

208
00:24:18,580 --> 00:24:22,520
You can see the operation moment clearly.

209
00:24:24,420 --> 00:24:33,580
Take the load off and the chip switches to limited consumption with minimum duty cycle.

210
00:24:36,260 --> 00:24:49,600
I screw the 300 W back in and we see the duty cycle ramping up with the load.

211
00:24:50,700 --> 00:24:54,920
Consumption went up too — meaning the converter is fully working.

212
00:24:57,480 --> 00:25:04,560
Now, the question: why all this complexity just to power a Tesla?

213
00:25:06,720 --> 00:25:15,480
Why does this converter need to have exactly the characteristics shown on the schematic?

214
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:17,380
Here's what's happening.

215
00:25:18,240 --> 00:25:26,660
When the Tesla is running on this system, you need to set its operating power point.

216
00:25:28,600 --> 00:25:31,440
The system has to stay balanced.

217
00:25:31,760 --> 00:25:44,420
If we feed it too much voltage, what happens is the Tesla starts overdriving the process in the resonator itself.

218
00:25:44,680 --> 00:25:49,220
On the grenade we have a current amplitude peak.

219
00:25:49,340 --> 00:25:52,820
You'll see a dip instead — it ends up suppressing it.

220
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:06,020
If the voltage is too low, we don't get good interaction and current in the system won't ramp up either.

221
00:26:07,560 --> 00:26:11,340
This is done by adjusting the Tesla's supply specifically.

222
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:32,100
And by the way, once you've maxed out what the voltage-setting resistor can give you, you can also smoothly trim the maximum duty cycle with this other resistor.

223
00:26:32,100 --> 00:26:33,380
The duty cycle limit.

224
00:26:34,540 --> 00:26:44,860
This resistor on the chip sets the final width of the duty cycle.

225
00:26:46,320 --> 00:26:49,200
You can set whatever you want.

226
00:26:49,820 --> 00:26:59,740
If you don't need a really powerful converter, you can set the duty cycle around 35–40% with this resistor.

227
00:27:03,570 --> 00:27:06,070
Good luck to everyone building one.
